# WHAT IT IS
#   lc39 is the canonical Node.js service launcher for the
#   Mia-Platform cloud-native development platform.  It wraps
#   any Fastify-based service module and provides:
#     • OpenTelemetry-instrumented service boot (the SDK is
#       initialized BEFORE the service module is required, so
#       Fastify's HTTP layer + DB clients + downstream HTTP
#       calls all auto-instrument cleanly via
#       `@opentelemetry/auto-instrumentations-node`)
#     • a built-in Prometheus `/-/metrics` endpoint
#     • a built-in Swagger / OpenAPI `/documentation` endpoint
#     • opinionated config-via-env via dotenv + dotenv-expand
#     • route prefixing via `--prefix`
#     • coordinated graceful shutdown
#
#   Mia-Platform itself standardizes on lc39 as the launcher
#   for every Node.js service it generates, so the typical
#   workflow inside a Mia-Platform project is:
#     `lc39 ./index.js --port 3000 --enable-tracing true \
#           --prefix /myservice --expose-metrics true`
#   with the Fastify service module exporting the default
#   plugin signature `module.exports = async function (
#   fastify, opts) { ... }`.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from bin/cli.js commander.js
#                       chain; extracted via `gh api repos/
#                       mia-platform/lc39/contents/bin/cli.js`)
#
#   lc39 <FILE> [OPTIONS]
#
#   Positional:
#     <FILE>                         Fastify service entry-
#                                    point JavaScript file
#                                    (must export the standard
#                                    Fastify plugin signature)
#
#   Options:
#     -v, --version                  Show version
#     -p, --port <PORT>              The port on which the
#                                    service will listen
#                                    [default: 3000]
#     -x, --prefix <PREFIX>          The routes prefix to add
#                                    to the service
#     -l, --log-level <LEVEL>        The log level to set
#                                    (passed through to
#                                    Fastify's pino logger)
#     -e, --env-path [ENVFILE]       The env file path
#                                    (dotenv + dotenv-expand)
#     --expose-metrics <BOOL>        Expose /-/metrics for
#                                    Prometheus  [default:
#                                    true]
#     --enable-tracing <BOOL>        Enable tracing  (preview
#                                    feature — new releases may
#                                    include breaking changes)
#                                    [default: false]
#     --expose-documentation <BOOL>  Expose /documentation
#                                    (Swagger UI)  [default:
#                                    true]
#
#   Standard commander auto-flags:
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   Direct dependency on `@opentelemetry/sdk-node ^0.218.0` +
#   `@opentelemetry/auto-instrumentations-node` +
#   `@opentelemetry/sdk-trace-base` declared in package.json —
#   `@opentelemetry/sdk-node` is THE canonical TypeScript /
#   JavaScript Node-side SDK for the CNCF OpenTelemetry
#   specification, maintained by the OpenTelemetry community
#   at the open-telemetry/opentelemetry-js repository (3,000+
#   stars; the predominant typed Node SDK for traces / metrics
#   / logs that every Node.js observability pipeline ends up
#   depending on — used by mia-platform/lc39, langwatch/
#   langwatch, takt, IBM/ibmi-mcp-server, proffesor-for-
#   testing/agentic-qe, genkit-ai/genkit, TrafficGuard/typedai,
#   AndriyKalashnykov/dapr-nodejs-nextjs, cadence-workflow/
#   cadence-web, livekit/agents-js, refly-ai/refly, and
#   dozens of other production Node.js applications that emit
#   OTLP telemetry).  `@opentelemetry/sdk-node` exposes the
#   typed `NodeSDK` factory:
#     `new NodeSDK({
#        resource: new Resource({
#           [SemanticResourceAttributes.SERVICE_NAME]:
#               'lc39-service',
#        }),
#        traceExporter: new OTLPTraceExporter({
#           url: 'http://localhost:4318/v1/traces',
#        }),
#        metricReader: new PeriodicExportingMetricReader({
#           exporter: new OTLPMetricExporter({ url: ... }),
#        }),
#        logRecordProcessor: new BatchLogRecordProcessor(
#           new OTLPLogExporter({ url: ... })),
#        instrumentations: getNodeAutoInstrumentations(),
#        contextManager: new AsyncLocalStorageContextManager(),
#        textMapPropagator: new W3CTraceContextPropagator(),
#     })` — followed by `sdk.start()` and a graceful
#   `sdk.shutdown()` on `SIGTERM` / `SIGINT`.  The companion
#   `@opentelemetry/auto-instrumentations-node` (which lc39
#   also direct-depends on) auto-wires every common Node.js
#   library — `http` / `https` / `fastify` / `express` /
#   `mongodb` / `redis` / `pg` / `mysql` / `aws-sdk` /
#   `grpc-js` / `kafkajs` / `nestjs` / `pino` / `winston` /
#   etc. — so userspace code stays untouched.
#   `@opentelemetry/api` (the spec-only zero-dependency surface)
#   provides the typed `trace.getTracer("module.name")` /
#   `trace.getActiveSpan()` / `context.active()` /
#   `context.with(ctx, fn)` /
#   `propagation.inject(ctx, carrier, setter)` /
#   `propagation.extract(ctx, carrier, getter)` /
#   `metrics.getMeter("module.name")` /
#   `logs.getLogger("module.name")` accessors that user code
#   uses to record custom spans / measurements / log records
#   on top of the auto-instrumented baseline.
#   lc39's `lib/otel-instrumentation.js` constructs a NodeSDK
#   per service-launcher invocation, starts it BEFORE
#   requiring the Fastify service module (so the
#   auto-instrumentation hooks register before any
#   instrumented library is loaded), and wires the
#   `--enable-tracing` flag into the SDK's start/no-op gate.
#   Verified via:
#     gh api repos/mia-platform/lc39/contents/package.json
#       → "@opentelemetry/sdk-node": "^0.218.0"
#       → "@opentelemetry/auto-instrumentations-node"
#       → "@opentelemetry/sdk-trace-base"
#       → "commander", "fastify", "fastify-metrics",
#         "fastify-plugin", "dotenv", "dotenv-expand"
#       → bin: { "lc39": "bin/cli.js" }
#       → license: "Apache-2.0"
#     gh api repos/mia-platform/lc39/contents/bin/cli.js
#       → const instrumentOTel = require(
#                          '../lib/otel-instrumentation')
#       → program.name('lc39').version(version, '-v,
#                                                --version')
#       → program.arguments('<file>').description(
#                          'lc39 is the Mia-Platform
#                          Node.js service launcher')
#       → options: -p/--port (default 3000), -x/--prefix,
#                   -l/--log-level, -e/--env-path,
#                   --expose-metrics (default true),
#                   --enable-tracing (default false),
#                   --expose-documentation (default true)
#       → const sdk = instrumentOTel(program.opts())
#       → require('../lib/launch-fastify')(...) is loaded
#         AFTER the NodeSDK initializes, so
#         auto-instrumentation hooks register before
#         the Fastify service module is required
#   This entry is the TS-Node=160 leader bump that CLOSES Axis
#   105 (OpenTelemetry observability) at 1/1/1 three-language
#   symmetry — triple-160 landmark and the 98th axis closed.
#   Pairings:
#     Rust=160   : alchemyplatform/rundler on opentelemetry-
#                  rust v0.28.0 + OTLP/gRPC  (_rundler, R1007
#                  — Axis 105 OPENED; R1007 Rust=160 round-
#                  number leader bump milestone)
#     Go=160     : bbkane/enventory on go.opentelemetry.io/
